00:00:38.694 --> 00:00:41.142
And in our circuit here,
we're gonna have a resistor

00:00:41.142 --> 00:00:42.142
of 330 ohms,

00:00:44.367 --> 00:00:48.455
and we'll make this battery three volts,

00:00:48.455 --> 00:00:51.122
so it's like two double-A cells.

00:00:54.307 --> 00:00:55.845
And what we wanna find out is

00:00:55.845 --> 00:00:58.611
how much current's gonna
flow around this circuit.

00:00:58.611 --> 00:01:00.981
And then we label this here,

00:01:00.981 --> 00:01:04.326
let me label the voltages
across our components.

00:01:04.326 --> 00:01:07.826
We'll have VD, which is this voltage here,

00:01:09.676 --> 00:01:13.640
and we'll have VR, which
is the resistor voltage,

00:01:13.640 --> 00:01:16.827
and that's that voltage right there.

00:01:16.827 --> 00:01:20.895
So now I'm gonna show you
a plot of the iv curve

00:01:20.895 --> 00:01:22.181
of our diode.

00:01:22.181 --> 00:01:24.147
You can see right here, around 0.7 volts,

00:01:24.147 --> 00:01:27.811
the current rises rapidly
when there's 0.7 volts

00:01:27.811 --> 00:01:29.228
across the diode.

00:01:30.325 --> 00:01:32.557
And let's start out by analyzing this,

00:01:32.557 --> 00:01:35.191
let's start with the same
tools that we always have,

00:01:35.191 --> 00:01:38.272
which is, let's try to
write some current laws

00:01:38.272 --> 00:01:39.974
for these two things.

00:01:39.974 --> 00:01:42.135
So for the diode, we write a current law

00:01:42.135 --> 00:01:43.931
that looks like this.

00:01:43.931 --> 00:01:46.598
The current is equal to IS times

00:01:48.111 --> 00:01:49.028
e to the qv

00:01:50.823 --> 00:01:51.656
on kT

00:01:53.579 --> 00:01:54.877
minus one.

00:01:54.877 --> 00:01:57.595
So that's the iv
characteristic for the diode,

00:01:57.595 --> 00:01:59.345
where this is V diode

00:02:01.950 --> 00:02:06.806
right there, and the corresponding
equation for the resistor

00:02:06.806 --> 00:02:08.639
is i equals V resistor

00:02:10.996 --> 00:02:11.829
over 330

00:02:14.939 --> 00:02:15.772
ohms.

00:02:16.925 --> 00:02:19.139
That's just Ohm's Law for the resistor,

00:02:19.139 --> 00:02:22.556
and i in both cases is this i right here.

00:02:24.524 --> 00:02:27.018
Now if I wanted to, I could
set these two expressions

00:02:27.018 --> 00:02:31.185
equal to each other and
solve somehow for VD and VR,

00:02:32.055 --> 00:02:33.847
but what we're gonna do instead
is we're gonna solve this

00:02:33.847 --> 00:02:36.956
by graphing, by a graphical method.

00:02:36.956 --> 00:02:39.064
Here's a graph for the diode,

00:02:39.064 --> 00:02:42.166
and this is the VD scale, this is V diode,

00:02:42.166 --> 00:02:43.999
and this is i up here.

00:02:45.041 --> 00:02:47.318
And so what I wanna do is I
wanna plot the resistor curve

00:02:47.318 --> 00:02:48.267
around here as well.

00:02:48.267 --> 00:02:50.864
I wanna plot the resistor iv curve

00:02:50.864 --> 00:02:52.843
on this same plot.

00:02:52.843 --> 00:02:56.533
Now, in this expression,
I have VR instead of VD,

00:02:56.533 --> 00:02:59.783
so let me see if I can work on VR here.

00:03:04.685 --> 00:03:08.136
Let me try to figure
out VR in terms of VD.

00:03:08.136 --> 00:03:09.636
So I can derive VR

00:03:10.590 --> 00:03:11.757
as three volts

00:03:13.428 --> 00:03:14.261
minus VD.

00:03:20.299 --> 00:03:22.566
And let's put this into
this i expression here.

00:03:22.566 --> 00:03:25.272
The Ohm's Law expression now becomes

00:03:25.272 --> 00:03:26.105
i equals,

00:03:27.912 --> 00:03:30.829
VR is replaced with three minus VD,

00:03:33.810 --> 00:03:35.310
all over 330 ohms.

00:03:38.478 --> 00:03:40.906
And let's work on this a little more.

00:03:40.906 --> 00:03:41.739
i equals

00:03:45.233 --> 00:03:46.400
three over 330

00:03:48.661 --> 00:03:50.161
minus VD over 330,

00:03:55.092 --> 00:03:59.344
and this is starting to look
like the equation of a line.

00:03:59.344 --> 00:04:03.511
Let me write this to recognize
it as a equation of a line.

00:04:05.004 --> 00:04:05.837
Minus VD

00:04:08.572 --> 00:04:09.405
over 330

00:04:14.604 --> 00:04:17.771
plus three over 330 is nine milliamps.

00:04:23.903 --> 00:04:26.314
So this is the equation
of a line, and the slope

00:04:26.314 --> 00:04:29.397
is right here, is minus one over 330,

00:04:30.932 --> 00:04:34.099
and the i-intercept is nine milliamps.

00:04:35.793 --> 00:04:37.521
So let's see if we can plot this line.

00:04:37.521 --> 00:04:40.435
This is actually called a

00:04:40.435 --> 00:04:41.268
Load Line.

00:04:44.183 --> 00:04:47.227
That's just a nickname for
this kind of expression

00:04:47.227 --> 00:04:50.615
that you get when you
have a resistor connected

00:04:50.615 --> 00:04:53.770
to a fixed power supply
above and the resistor is

00:04:53.770 --> 00:04:55.520
hanging down from it.

00:04:56.620 --> 00:04:59.234
You get this characteristic
equation of a line

00:04:59.234 --> 00:05:03.718
that has a negative slope,
which is really distinctive.

00:05:03.718 --> 00:05:05.577
Let's see if we can plot this line.

00:05:05.577 --> 00:05:08.619
Now, it's a line, so all we
have to do is find two points

00:05:08.619 --> 00:05:12.261
that solve the line and then
we'll be able to draw the line.

00:05:12.261 --> 00:05:14.785
So if I set VD equal to zero,

00:05:14.785 --> 00:05:17.202
then i equals nine milliamps.

00:05:18.427 --> 00:05:22.195
So here's VD equal to
zero, and it'll go through

00:05:22.195 --> 00:05:23.951
nine milliamps.

00:05:23.951 --> 00:05:24.784
