00:05:43.957 --> 00:05:47.225
and i equal zero means there's
no current in this resistor,

00:05:47.225 --> 00:05:50.689
which means there's no voltage
drop across that resistor.

00:05:50.689 --> 00:05:53.626
And that means that this voltage here

00:05:53.626 --> 00:05:56.659
is the same as this voltage here.

00:05:56.659 --> 00:05:57.960
And I know the voltage here,

00:05:57.960 --> 00:06:00.847
the voltage here is three volts,

00:06:00.847 --> 00:06:04.101
so that means the voltage
here is three volts,

00:06:04.101 --> 00:06:08.254
and that's because I
know the current is zero.

00:06:08.254 --> 00:06:11.372
So let's go over and put
that point on a line.

00:06:11.372 --> 00:06:14.372
So when i is zero, v is three volts.

00:06:15.344 --> 00:06:18.863
So there's another point on the line.

00:06:18.863 --> 00:06:20.784
And now we have two points
and we can draw a line

00:06:20.784 --> 00:06:21.784
between 'em,

00:06:22.984 --> 00:06:23.817
like that.

00:06:28.134 --> 00:06:31.462
And what we've drawn is the Load Line

00:06:31.462 --> 00:06:33.629
for this 330-ohm resistor.

00:06:35.522 --> 00:06:37.527
You remember, back over
here we said we could solve

00:06:37.527 --> 00:06:39.669
these two equations by setting the two is

00:06:39.669 --> 00:06:41.190
equal to each other,

00:06:41.190 --> 00:06:44.332
and that's basically where
do these two lines intersect?

00:06:44.332 --> 00:06:46.832
And they intersect right here.

00:06:47.919 --> 00:06:50.836
That's the solution to our problem.

00:06:52.171 --> 00:06:54.220
So this intersection
point is the solution.

00:06:54.220 --> 00:06:56.812
It's where the resistor
current and the diode current

00:06:56.812 --> 00:06:59.428
are the same, and that's that point there.

